      "id": "MATH_RA_CAUCHY_STRUCTURED",
      "subject": "math",
      "unit": "Real Analysis",
      "topic": "Cauchy sequences",
      "year": "2024",
      "type": "structured",
      "body": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Prove that every convergent sequence in \\(\\mathbb{R}\\) is a Cauchy sequence."
        }
      ],
      "answer": { "mode": "self_mark", "value": null },
      "explanation": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Let \\((x_n)\\) converge to \\(L\\). For any \\(\\epsilon \\gt 0\\), choose \\(N\\) such that \\(|x_n - L| \\lt \\epsilon/2\\) for all \\(n \\ge N\\). If \\(m,n \\ge N\\), then \\(|x_n - x_m| \\le |x_n - L| + |x_m - L| \\lt \\epsilon\\). Hence \\((x_n)\\) is Cauchy."
        }
      ],
      "source": { "pdf": "MA1014_2024.pdf", "page": 5, "qno": 2 },
      "status": "published"
    },
